      contextTitle: 'Backup versus sync',
      context: ['Backup aims to return to a previous state. Sync aims to keep the same files on multiple devices. If files are deleted or encrypted, sync can replicate the problem unless versioning exists.', 'NCSC and CISA recommend tested and separated backups. Cloud can be part of the strategy, but does not automatically replace a historical disconnected copy.'],
      decisionTitle: 'Advantages and limits',
      decision: ['Local backup on an external drive is fast, cheap and independent of the internet. Its weakness is being in the same place as the computer and possibly damaged, lost or connected during an attack.', 'Cloud protects against theft, fire or local disk failure, and helps recovery from another device. Its limits are quota, cost, privacy, upload speed and account dependence.'],
      practiceTitle: 'Recommended home design',
      practice: ['For important documents, combine cloud with versioning and a disconnected external drive. For large photos or videos, review storage cost and real upload time.', 'Encrypt backups containing sensitive documents, but store the key safely. A perfectly encrypted backup without the key is the same as lost data.'],
      steps: ['Classify files by importance and size.', 'Use cloud for availability and external drive for fast recovery.', 'Enable versioning or history if available.', 'Test restoration from both places.', 'Review quotas, costs and keys.'],
      tips: ['Do not keep the backup drive always connected.', 'Check cloud syncs the right folders.', 'Keep a list of accounts used for backup.'],
      warnings: ['Cloud depends on account recovery.', 'Local drive does not protect against fire or theft if beside the computer.', 'Without versioning you may sync accidental deletions.'],
      faq: [['Which is better?', 'There is no single winner. Local wins speed; cloud wins distance and availability.'], ['Can I use only cloud?', 'You can, but review versioning, account recovery and an extra copy for critical data.']],
